`? extends BaseEntity` means &quot;some specific, unknown subtype of `BaseEntity`&quot;. You can&#39;t pass it to the repository because as far as the compiler is concerned, `repository` might be a `BaseRepository&lt;Employee, Integer&gt;`, while `concreteEntities` might be a `List&lt;Contractor&gt;`. The solution is to use your type parameter `T` instead:

    public class MyClass&lt;T extends BaseEntity&gt; {
    
        BaseRepository&lt;T, Integer&gt; repository;
        
        public MyClass(BaseRepository&lt;T&gt; repository){
            this.repository = repository;
        }
    
        public void doSomething(List&lt;T&gt; concreteEntities){
            //...does something
            repository.saveAll(concreteEntities);
        }
    }

This ensures that no matter which subtype `T` represents, it&#39;s the same type across all uses for this instance.

See also:  
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2723397/what-is-pecs-producer-extends-consumer-super  
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/22860582/java-generics-wildcard-vs-type-parametere

