answers.body_markdown:
A database connection can also be assigned to flyway using **username**, **password** and **url**.
With these parameters the database connection used by flyway will be closed again when all scripts are migrated.

From a DataSource the needed parameters can be read, but that **is different for every implementation of the DataSource** interface which is provided from the environment.

---

The following example assumes that the **DataSource** is from a **Tomcat web server** environment (in Java 17):
```xml
&lt;dependency&gt;
    &lt;groupId&gt;org.apache.tomcat&lt;/groupId&gt;
    &lt;artifactId&gt;tomcat-dbcp&lt;/artifactId&gt;
    &lt;version&gt;10.0.8&lt;/version&gt;
    &lt;scope&gt;provided&lt;/scope&gt;
&lt;/dependency&gt;
```
```java
import org.apache.tomcat.dbcp.dbcp2.BasicDataSource;

[...]

private Flyway configureFlyway() {
    FluentConfiguration config = new FluentConfiguration();

    if (getDs() instanceof BasicDataSource tomcatBasicDataSource) {
        String username = tomcatBasicDataSource.getUsername();
        String password = tomcatBasicDataSource.getPassword();
        String url = tomcatBasicDataSource.getUrl();
        config.dataSource(url, username, password);
    }

    config.baselineOnMigrate(true);
    config.cleanDisabled(true);
    config.outOfOrder(true);
    config.validateMigrationNaming(true);
    config.validateOnMigrate(false);
    config.locations(SCRIPTS_PATH);
    config.loggers(LOGGER);

    return new Flyway(config);
}
```

---

FYI Flyway configuration can also be set via builder pattern (which is more compact):
```java
return Flyway.configure()
    .dataSource(url, username, password)
    .baselineOnMigrate(true)
    .cleanDisabled(true)
    .outOfOrder(true)
    .validateMigrationNaming(true)
    .validateOnMigrate(false)
    .locations(SCRIPTS_PATH)
    .loggers(LOGGER)
    .load();
```

